				<name type="primary" sortindex="1" value="古狼の荊 (Korou no Ibara)" />
			
						                           
						               													<description>Polygonotes's 7th card game, &amp;#229;&amp;#143;&amp;#164;&amp;#231;&amp;#139;&amp;#188;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#174;&amp;#232;&amp;#141;&amp;#138; (&amp;quot;Thorns of the Ancient Wolves&amp;quot;), was made around the themes of distrust and reading other people. Though the rules are simple and easy to learn, it has a high ceiling for strategy and will bring you back to play it again and again.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;mdash;description from the publisher (translated)&amp;#10;&amp;#10;In Thorns of the Ancient Wolves, players are hunters caught between the conflict of a mad king trying to exterminate the ancient wolves of the nearby forest, and the wolves ready to go to war to protect their home. Each faction is represented by a suit of cards- red for the wolves and blue for the kingdom.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;When it is your turn, you draw a card from a face-down pool of 3 and choose a card to play from your hand. Cards are worth points and have special effects. When it is the end of a player's turn and they have 10 or more points from a single faction in their play area, the round ends and that faction is scored as positive for all players- with the losing faction being scored as negative for everyone as well. Players tally their points and add (or subtract) them to victory points that persist between rounds, then begin a new round. If at the end of a round a  player has 15 or more points, the player with the highest victory point total wins.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;mdash;user summmary&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
